Udacity Data Analysis Nanodegree¶

Project 5: Communicate data findings¶

Predicting flight delays¶

by Juanita Smith¶

Investigation Overview¶

Have you ever been stuck in an airport because your flight was delayed and wondered if you could have predicted it if you'd had more data? This is our chance to find out!
In this investigation, I wanted to explore which characteristics could predict delays the most. Several avenues were explored: seasonality patterns, airport/carrier relationships, distance (short haul vs long haul flights), etc.

Key insights:
  • 21% of flights are delayed
  • Top airports and carriers causing delays
  • Seasonal peaks are the biggest factor for delays
  • Deep dive into specific airports/carriers causing the most delays
  • Distance is the most distinguishing factor for delays


Dataset Overview

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, with reasons for delays, from 1987 to 2008. Due to large data volume, only years 2003 - 2007 will analysed in this project.

Distribution of flights

Around 77% of flights are on time, where as 21% are delayed. Only 2% of flights are cancelled or diverted.

Seasonal Analysis¶

When is the best time of year/day of week/time of day to fly to minimise delays?¶

Seasonal Analysis: Monthly Distribution

In the first plot on the left in blue, which focus on the distribution of delayed flights, there are 2 strong peaks visible:
  • Christmas period in December - March
  • During summer months June - August


In the second plot on the right in grey, which plot the distribution of all flights, there is not much variation in the total flights per month even in the peak periods.
Conclusion: Airports are more busy during peak periods, even though number of flights do not increase. This might be due to an increase in passengers in airports on fully booked flights.

Seasonal Analysis: Weekday Distribution

In the first plot on the left in blue, which focus on the distribution of delayed flights, delays are more likely to happen on Mondays, Thursdays and Fridays.

In the second plot on the right in grey, which plot the distribution of all flights, weekdays have the same number of flights, weekends are more quiet
Conclusion: - Most delays happens on weekdays on Mondays, Thursdays and Fridays. Tuesdays and Saturdays are the quietest days. Airports are less busy with less delays on weekends.

Seasonal Analysis: Time of day Distribution

In the first plot on the left in blue, which focus on the distribution of delayed flights, delays are more likely to happen on Mondays, Thursdays and Fridays.

In the second plot on the right in grey, which plot the distribution of all flights, weekdays have the same number of flights, weekends are more quiet.
Conclusion: Delays are growing progressively throughout the day starting at 6am until 8pm whereas the total number of flights stay constant. Delay peaks are between for 5-8pm. From 8pm, both the delays and number of flights decrease.

Seasonal Analysis: Trend and Time series using statmodels¶

Conclusion:
  • There is an upwards trend in delayed flights year upon year.
  • There is a strong seasonal pattern re-occuring every year. The trend is removed from the time series and the average of this de-trended series for each period is the returned seasonal component

Which airports cause the most delays ?¶

Compare how many flights are delayed vs on_time in departure airports

Conclusion:

The busiest departure airports are ATL, ORD, DFW and EWR.
From a proportional perspective, JFK, PHL, EWR, ORD have over 40% of their flights delayed on departure

Which carriers cause the most delays ?¶

How many flights are delayed vs on_time by carrier ?

Conclusion:

Southwest Airlines, American Airlines and Delta Airlines are by the biggest carriers

Delayed flights from a proportional perspective:
  • Atlantic Southeast with 36% of their flights delayed,
  • Jet Blue with 32%,
  • Mesa Airlines at 31% and
  • Americaln Eagle at 31%

What is the relationship between carriers and the departure airports they serve ?

  • The bottom right quadrant (problem quandrant) contains the carriers and airport combinations with the most average delays, the darker green/blue area is clearly distinguishable.
  • The top 3 biggest carriers, have below average and consistant delays accross all airports and appear in the top half of the heat plot
  • The top 3 businest departure airports are positioned on the right of the heatplot. However these airports are not doing consistantly 'bad', carriers in the top half are still doing well at these airports.

Conclusion:
Why are certain carriers performing bad at certain airports ? The fact that the same carriers does well at airports in left quadrant, but worse at these airports on the right, indicate it must be a carrier/location combination where some carriers might have lower priority at some airports?

Summary¶

  • Delays decrease in spring/autumn months.
  • Airports are more busy during peak periods, even though number of flights do not increase. This might be due to an increase in passengers on fully booked flights, thus more passengers in airports
